result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration - 4th Offense in 5 Years [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While Under the Influence (4th w/in 5 yrs)] and Operating A Motor Vehicle While Intoxicated - 4th Offense in 5 years [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While Under the Influence (4th w/in 5 yrs)]. The defendant was found guilty of Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration - 4th Offense in 5 Years [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While Under the Influence (4th w/in 5 yrs)] and the other charge, Operating A Motor Vehicle While Intoxicated - 4th Offense in 5 years [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While Under the Influence (4th w/in 5 yrs)] was dismissed by the court.

  • Landon David Berg was found guilty of Operating With Prohibited Alcohol Concentration - 4th Offense in 5 Years [Modifiers: Penalty - Operating While Under the Influence (4th w/in 5 yrs)], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: In the event that the defendant is discharged from probation with outstanding financial obligations, the supervising agent SHALL notify the court 10 days prior to the revocation or discharge.  A civil judgment SHALL be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.  07-27-2017:  Per correspondence with Judge's approval - Probation to be terminated upon defendant's payment of unpaid court costs and fines which now total $885.36.

Any vehicle(s) titled in the Defendant's name and/or any vehicle(s) operated by the Defendant are subject to an ignition interlock device.  The ignition interlock requirement becomes effective when the Defendant applies for a license.
Defendant to receive an alcohol assessment and comply with any driver's safety plan.

miscConds.notes: Defendant to pay court costs, including the Blood Draw Fee and the Ignition Interlock Surcharge.  8-26-16:  Court orders DNA surcharge to be assessed.
Defendant not to consume or possess alcohol or enter bars or taverns.
Defendant is to comply with any treatment/programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and agent.

timeConds.notes: After the 1st 48 hours, Defendant is eligible for huber privileges for employment.  Defendant is eligible for Electronic Monitoring.
